{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-post-template-jsx","path":"/python-numpy-array","result":{"data":{"markdownRemark":{"html":"<h1 id=\"numpy-in-python\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#numpy-in-python\" aria-label=\"numpy in python permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>NumPy in Python</h1>\n<p>let us first learn what is NumPy:</p>\n<p>NumPy is a python library used for working with arrays. It also has functions for working in the domain of linear algebra, Fourier transform, and matrices. NumPy is an open-source project and we can use it freely. NumPy stands for Numerical Python.</p>\n<h2 id=\"why-should-we-use-numpy\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#why-should-we-use-numpy\" aria-label=\"why should we use numpy permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>why should we use NumPy?</h2>\n<p>In Python, we have lists that serve the purpose of arrays, but they are slow to process. NumPy aims to provide an array object that is up to 50 times faster than traditional Python lists. The array object in NumPy is called ndarray. It provides a lot of supporting functions that make working with ndarray very easy.</p>\n<h2 id=\"where-is-numpy-used\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#where-is-numpy-used\" aria-label=\"where is numpy used permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Where is NumPy used?</h2>\n<p>Python NumPy arrays provide tools for integrating C, C++, etc. It is also useful in linear algebra, random number capability, etc. NumPy array can also be used as an efficient multi-dimensional container for generic data. </p>\n<h2 id=\"why-is-numpy-faster-than-lists\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#why-is-numpy-faster-than-lists\" aria-label=\"why is numpy faster than lists permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Why is NumPy Faster than lists?</h2>\n<p>NumPy arrays are stored at one continuous place in memory unlike lists, so processes can access and manipulate them very efficiently.</p>\n<p>now let us learn how to create an array using NumPy:</p>\n<h2 id=\"create-a-numpy-ndarray-object\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#create-a-numpy-ndarray-object\" aria-label=\"create a numpy ndarray object permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Create a NumPy ndarray Object</h2>\n<p>NumPy is used to work with arrays. The array object in NumPy is called ndarray.\nWe can create a NumPy ndarray object by using the array() function.</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"python\"><pre class=\"language-python\"><code class=\"language-python\"><span class=\"token keyword\">import</span> numpy <span class=\"token keyword\">as</span> np\n\narr <span class=\"token operator\">=</span> np<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span>array<span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">[</span><span class=\"token number\">1</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span> <span class=\"token number\">2</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span> <span class=\"token number\">3</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span> <span class=\"token number\">4</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span> <span class=\"token number\">5</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">]</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span>\n\n<span class=\"token keyword\">print</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span>arr<span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span>\n\n<span class=\"token keyword\">print</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token builtin\">type</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span>arr<span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span></code></pre></div>\n<p>OUTPUT:\n[1 2 3 4 5]\n&#x3C;class 'numpy.ndarray'></p>\n<h2 id=\"joining-numpy-arrays\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#joining-numpy-arrays\" aria-label=\"joining numpy arrays permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Joining NumPy Arrays</h2>\n<p>Joining means putting contents of two or more arrays in a single array.\nIn SQL we join tables based on a key, whereas in NumPy we join arrays by axes.\nWe pass a sequence of arrays that we want to join to the concatenate() function, along with the axis. If the axis is not explicitly passed, it is taken as 0.</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"python\"><pre class=\"language-python\"><code class=\"language-python\"><span class=\"token keyword\">import</span> numpy <span class=\"token keyword\">as</span> np\n\narr1 <span class=\"token operator\">=</span> np<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span>array<span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">[</span><span class=\"token number\">1</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span> <span class=\"token number\">2</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span> <span class=\"token number\">3</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">]</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span>\n\narr2 <span class=\"token operator\">=</span> np<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span>array<span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">[</span><span class=\"token number\">4</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span> <span class=\"token number\">5</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span> <span class=\"token number\">6</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">]</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span>\n\narr <span class=\"token operator\">=</span> np<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span>concatenate<span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span>arr1<span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span> arr2<span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span>\n\n<span class=\"token keyword\">print</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span>arr<span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span></code></pre></div>\n<p>OUTPUT:\n[1 2 3 4 5 6]</p>\n<h2 id=\"splitting-numpy-arrays\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#splitting-numpy-arrays\" aria-label=\"splitting numpy arrays permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Splitting NumPy Arrays</h2>\n<p>Splitting is the reverse operation of Joining.\nJoining merges multiple arrays into one and Splitting breaks one array into multiple.\nWe use array_split() for splitting arrays, we pass it the array we want to split and the number of splits.\nSplit the array into 3 parts:</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"python\"><pre class=\"language-python\"><code class=\"language-python\"><span class=\"token keyword\">import</span> numpy <span class=\"token keyword\">as</span> np\n\narr <span class=\"token operator\">=</span> np<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span>array<span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">[</span><span class=\"token number\">1</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span> <span class=\"token number\">2</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span> <span class=\"token number\">3</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span> <span class=\"token number\">4</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span> <span class=\"token number\">5</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span> <span class=\"token number\">6</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">]</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span>\n\nnewarr <span class=\"token operator\">=</span> np<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span>array_split<span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span>arr<span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span> <span class=\"token number\">3</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span>\n\n<span class=\"token keyword\">print</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span>newarr<span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span></code></pre></div>\n<p>OUTPUT:\n[array([1, 2]), array([3, 4]), array([5, 6])]</p>\n<h2 id=\"sorting-arrays\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#sorting-arrays\" aria-label=\"sorting arrays permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Sorting Arrays</h2>\n<p>Sorting means putting elements in an ordered sequence.\nOrdered sequence is any sequence that has an order corresponding to elements, like numeric or alphabetical, ascending, or descending.\nThe NumPy ndarray object has a function called sort(), that will sort a specified array.</p>\n<p>Sort the array:</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"python\"><pre class=\"language-python\"><code class=\"language-python\"><span class=\"token keyword\">import</span> numpy <span class=\"token keyword\">as</span> np\n\narr <span class=\"token operator\">=</span> np<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span>array<span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">[</span><span class=\"token number\">3</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span> <span class=\"token number\">2</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span> <span class=\"token number\">0</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span> <span class=\"token number\">1</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">]</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span>\n\n<span class=\"token keyword\">print</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span>np<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span>sort<span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span>arr<span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span></code></pre></div>\n<p>OUTPUT:\n[0 1 2 3]</p>\n<h2 id=\"conclusion\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#conclusion\" aria-label=\"conclusion permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>conclusion:</h2>\n<p>so this was a 1-minute read article on NumPy. Hope this article helps you to get started with NumPy.</p>\n<p>Thank you!! </p>","timeToRead":3,"excerpt":"NumPy in Python let us first learn what is NumPy: NumPy is a python library used for working with arrays. It also has functions for working…","frontmatter":{"title":"Python NumPy Array","date":"2020-10-28 19:28:00 +0530","categories":["python"],"tags":["Python","NumpPy","array"],"description":null,"keywords":"Python, NumpPy, array","author":"Daita Sur","cover":{"childImageSharp":{"fixed":{"base64":"data:image/png;base64,","width":204,"height":132,"src":"/static/c4fa3c5851be4bf4f2f39daf2e691d3b/02521/python.png","srcSet":"/static/c4fa3c5851be4bf4f2f39daf2e691d3b/02521/python.png 1x"}}}},"fields":{"slug":"/python-numpy-array","date":"2020-10-28T13:58:00.000Z"}}},"pageContext":{"slug":"/python-numpy-array","nexttitle":"Useful Python libraries For Natural Processing","nextslug":"/useful-python-libraries-for-natural-processing","prevtitle":"Lesser Known HTML5 Tricks","prevslug":"/lesser-known-html5-tricks","tagList":["abstraction","OOP","Class","java","collection","API","Map","HashMap","LinkedHashMap","TreeMap","Python","cli","args","argparse","javascript","es6","beginner","codenewbie","Primary_key","implementation","Composite_key","language-support","localization","internationalization","linux","file permissions","Project Euler","Algortithms","SQL","database","commands","GO","Datatypes","Variables","Constants","HTML5","Web development","tricks","NumpPy","array","python","NLP","libraries","text processing","go","golang","data-structure","optimization","java 7","Java 8","comparison","mkdir(make-dir) and rmdir(remove-dir command) command","nodejs","backend","frontend","postgres","mac","installation","games","gamedev","memory","html","bootstrap","web development","data","strings","final","finally","finalize","Git","GitLens","VS Code Extension","CSS","CSS Variables","Images","Image Display","JavaScript","sort","localeCompare","Responsive Fonts","CSS Fonts","interface","default method","static static","plot","spring boot","c